In this tutorial you did the scraping, cleaning and analyzing in one pass. I do a lot of scraping and prefer to take them one at a time, with the first step downloading the web data in a local database where I can refer to it at anytime for analysis. But connecting to a db is another topic...

I also want to leave a tip about explicitly identifying wanted data in the html. You were find various tags from the entire soup, but most of the time there are multiple tables as well as other tags. Looking at the example html (which, as you point out, the reader can access by right licking and selecting 'inspect') I quickly noticed that the table of interest was assigned an id with a value of 'individualResults'. Reading only this table saves headaches of unwittingly grabbing data from the wrong table. Once the intended table has been isolated the rows and columns can be looped through. 

